  "doi": "10.1038/s41467-018-03321-w",
  "title": "Divergent T-cell receptor recognition modes of a HLA-I restricted extended tumour-associated peptide.",
  "journal": "Nature communications",
  "year": 2018,
  "authors": "Chan KF, Gully BS, Gras S, Beringer DX, Kjer-Nielsen L, Cebon J, McCluskey J, Chen W, Rossjohn J."
 },
 "executive_summary": "Two structurally distinct TCRs derived from a polyclonal T-cell repertoire recognize HLA-B*07:02 presenting a 13-amino-acid tumor-associated peptide (NY-ESO-1\u2086\u2080\u208b\u2087\u2082), despite HLA-I molecules typically binding only 8\u201310 amino acid peptides. The TCRs employ divergent binding modes, with differential engagement of the extended peptide and variable conformational changes at the TCR-pMHC interface. This work demonstrates that flexibility at the TCR-pHLA-I interface enables polyclonal recognition of extended tumor epitopes, clarifying how T cells can tolerate structural variation while targeting cancer-associated antigens and informing strategies for TCR engineering in neoantigen-directed immunotherapy.",
